{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17519709","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17519709"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:02+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T14:15:02+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13064"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"13064","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/13064"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.07,0.01,0.63,0.04,0.25]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"5501"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107961"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"5501","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/5501"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question","status":"accepted","createdAt":"2023-06-24T16:25:13+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T11:44:48+09:30","updatedAction":"commented","acceptedAt":"2023-10-16T15:30:12+10:30","editorNotifiedAt":null,"feedbackAt":"2025-09-23 20:32:28"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13064"}},"updatedBy":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"16432"}},"author":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"6678"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90374"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"10"},{"type":"tags","id":"66"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"225"},{"type":"tags","id":"2341"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"9360"},{"type":"contributions","id":"10100"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13439"},{"type":"contributions","id":"13762"},{"type":"contributions","id":"14992"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37064"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38466"},{"type":"contributions","id":"38467"},{"type":"contributions","id":"40268"}]},"lastContribution":{"data":null},"lastRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90374"}},"lastActivity":{"data":null},"lastFeedback":{"data":null}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"107961","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/107961"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 26-year-old man presents to the Emergency Department accompanied by his concerned partner. She reports that over the last month he has stopped leaving the house and often comments that there are \u0022bad people\u0022 looking for him. She is worried that he has been isolating himself and that he will lose his job. He has a history of schizophrenia, diagnosed six months ago, and was initially started on oral olanzapine twice daily. This provided good control of his symptoms initially. However, on further questioning, he admits that he has only been taking the medication intermittently over the last month as he often forgets. He has no other significant medical history and takes no regular medications. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination, he appears anxious but is cooperative. His vital signs are within normal limits. Mental state examination reveals paranoid delusions but no hallucinations or thought disorder. He denies any thoughts of self-harm, suicidal ideation, or intent to harm others. It is decided that he would benefit from admission. \u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most appropriate management plan?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Switch to oral quetiapine once daily","Switch to lithium","Switch to risperidone as a depot injection","Switch to oral clozapine once daily","Add aripiprazole as a depot injection"],"correctOptions":[2],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe most appropriate management plan is to \u003Cstrong\u003Eswitch to risperidone as a depot injection\u003C/strong\u003E. This patient has demonstrated poor adherence to oral medication, which has led to a relapse of his schizophrenia symptoms. According to current therapeutic guidelines, depot antipsychotic injections should be considered for patients who have difficulty adhering to oral medication regimens. The guidelines specifically recommend that when non-adherence is a significant issue, switching to a long-acting injectable antipsychotic can improve treatment outcomes and reduce relapse rates. Risperidone depot would provide consistent symptom control without the need for daily tablets, addressing the patient\u0027s adherence issues.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to oral quetiapine\u003C/strong\u003E once daily is unlikely to solve the adherence problem. While quetiapine can be effective for schizophrenia, the patient\u0027s issue is not the efficacy of the medication but rather his ability to take it consistently.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to lithium\u003C/strong\u003E is not appropriate in this case. Lithium is primarily used as a mood stabiliser in bipolar disorder and is not a first-line treatment for schizophrenia. It would not address the patient\u0027s psychotic symptoms effectively.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ESwitching to oral clozapine\u003C/strong\u003E is not indicated at this stage. Clozapine is reserved for treatment-resistant schizophrenia, typically after at least two trials of other antipsychotics have failed. This patient\u0027s symptoms were well-controlled when he was adherent to olanzapine, suggesting that his schizophrenia is not treatment-resistant.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EAdding aripiprazole as a depot injection\u003C/strong\u003E is not the best option. While aripiprazole is available as a depot formulation and can be effective in schizophrenia, adding a second antipsychotic is unnecessary if the patient has shown good response to a single agent. Moreover, it doesn\u0027t address the core issue of medication adherence as effectively as switching to a single depot antipsychotic.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EIn summary, switching to risperidone depot injection addresses both the need for effective antipsychotic treatment and the patient\u0027s difficulty with medication adherence. This approach is likely to provide the best chance of maintaining symptom control and preventing future relapses.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Depot antipsychotic injections are often helpful for patients with schizophrenia who have difficulty adhering to oral medication regimens.","Risperidone depot injection is a suitable option for patients with schizophrenia who have shown response to oral antipsychotics but struggle with adherence.","Clozapine is reserved for treatment-resistant schizophrenia and is not a first-line option for medication non-adherence."],"references":["Therapeutic Guidelines Limited. Psychotropic: recovery and relapse prevention in psychoses. Melbourne: Therapeutic Guidelines Limited; 2024. Available at: https://app.tg.org.au.acs.hcn.com.au/viewTopic?etgAccess=true\u0026guidelinePage=Psychotropic\u0026topicfile=recovery-relapse-prevention-psychoses\u0026guidelinename=Psychotropic\u0026sectionId=toc_d1e230","Blashki G, Hocking B, Stocky A, Keks N. Managing schizophrenia in general practice. In: RACGP [online]. 2004. Available from: https://www.racgp.org.au/getattachment/2257923a-da3d-4ed6-a610-49cc0bab6153/20040413blashki.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90374"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"13064"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"90374","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/90374"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-07-05T11:43:28+09:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T11:45:30+09:30","number":16,"notes":"","plagiarismCheckedAt":"2025-07-05T11:44:32+09:30","plagiarismScore":0,"plagiarismReportUrl":"https://emedici-copyleaks.syd1.digitaloceanspaces.com/plag